      <title>Rationalization of augment types and slots – improvements to set up future itemization</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&amp;message.id=212555#M212555</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The augment type and slot system is in need of serious revision and rationalization.  While each individual design decision may have made sense, the resulting set of augments and slots are currently inconsistent between expansions and limit the new itemization designer’s ability to appropriately design certain gear go forward.  The best description I’m aware of for the current slot types and sources of gear with those slots is &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://samanna.net/gen.info/augs.shtml"&gt;http://samanna.net/gen.info/augs.shtml&lt;/a&gt;.  The rest of this discussion pre-supposes the reader is aware of the current slot types and current augments in the game.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;I’d propose redesigning the slot types as follows:&lt;br&gt;All/1             Fits anywhere, jack of all trades, limited utility/power.&lt;br&gt;2                 Augments with stacking effect or beyond type 1 in power.&lt;br&gt;3                 Focus/foci and haste (non-stacking effects).&lt;br&gt;4                 Weapons: procs, bane damage, bonus damage.&lt;br&gt;5                 Reserved for future Weapon augments&lt;br&gt;6                 Slot- and diety specific.&lt;br&gt;7                 Base gear slot – variety of augments fit here&lt;br&gt;8                 High-end gear slot – top end raiding augments fit here.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Stacking effects: regeneration, mana regeneration, attack, damage shield, avoidance, accuracy, spell shielding, shielding, stun resistance, strikethrough, combat effects, and dot shielding.&lt;br&gt;Non-stacking effects:  all caster focii, all melee focii, haste, and bard instrument effects. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;For purposes of the following table, if an augment has both stacking effects and non-stacking effects, the stacking effects should be disregarded and it should be classified with augments with non-stacking effects.&lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt;Conversion of existing augments:&lt;br&gt;Existing augment                             Fits in new slots              Notes&lt;br&gt;Type 1/All                                         Type 1/All                     No change.&lt;br&gt;Type 2                                              Type All                       Upgrade to these augments.&lt;br&gt;Type 3 with stacking effect              Type 2, 7                         &lt;br&gt;Type 3 with non-stacking effect       Type 3, 7                        &lt;br&gt;Type 5                                              Type 4                         Simplification.&lt;br&gt;Type 6                                              Type 4                         Simplification.&lt;br&gt;Type 7 without effect                        Type 7                         No change.&lt;br&gt;Type 7 with stacking effect              Type 2, 7                      Adds type 2 dropped augs.&lt;br&gt;Type 7 with non-stacking effect       Type 3, 7                      Adds type 3 dropped augs.&lt;br&gt;Type 8 without effect                       Type 8                         No change.&lt;br&gt;Type 8 with stacking effect              Type 2, 8                      Adds type 2 dropped augs.&lt;br&gt;Type 8 with non-stacking effect       Type 3, 8                      Adds type 3 dropped augs.&lt;br&gt;Type 7, 8 without effect                   Type 7, 8                      No change.&lt;br&gt;Type 7, 8 with stacking effect          Type 2, 7, 8                 Adds type 2 dropped augs.&lt;br&gt;Type 7, 8 with non-stacking effect   Type 3, 7, 8                 Adds type 3 dropped augs.&lt;br&gt;Type 9                                              Type 2                         Simplification.&lt;br&gt;Type 9, 12                                        Type 2, 3&lt;br&gt;Type 7, 8, 12                                    Type 3, 7, 8&lt;br&gt;Type 11                                            Type 6&lt;br&gt;Type 12                                            Type 3&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Conversion of existing slots&lt;br&gt;Existing slot type            New slot type &lt;br&gt;1                                     1&lt;br&gt;2                                     3&lt;br&gt;3                                     7&lt;br&gt;4                                     4&lt;br&gt;5                                     4&lt;br&gt;6                                     4&lt;br&gt;7                                     7&lt;br&gt;8                                     8&lt;br&gt;9                                     2&lt;br&gt;11                                   6&lt;br&gt;12                                   3&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Exception:&lt;br&gt;If there are 2 type 2 slots on an item, one slot becomes the new type 2 and the other slot becomes the new type 3.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;I believe the proposed conversions are backwards compatible.  In other words, each and every revised piece of gear should be capable of holding the augments currently inserted into that piece of gear (after the revision to the augment types).   The only resulting inconsistency with the above proposed framework is I’m having to treat all OoW crafted augments and certain type 9/12 augments as if they had an non-stacking effect in order to allow them to remain in existing cultural armor pieces.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Advantages/disadvantages:&lt;br&gt;The vast majority of the proposed process can be automated.  It should not require significant developer time.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Having slot types be expansion dependent is not a good long term use of resources and makes future itemization more difficult.  5 slot types are currently associated exclusively with LDoN – 1,2,3,5 and 6.  1 slot type is strictly associated with DoN vendor armor and augments – 9.  DoN cultural currently uses 2 unique slot types: 11 and 12.  Slot 12 was carried into DoDH and PoR with the addition of the tradeskilled DoDH augments.  While there may have been some valid marketing reasons for how the augment system grew, there is no continuing reason why the existing structure of augment slots should reflect the expansion history so closely.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;I very much like the concept of the players being able to significantly customize gear.  I would prefer the players be given the tools to make choices than an itemization designer attempt to make the choices for them. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;For example, if the end-zone armor from the next expansion (whenever that is), is fairly basic armor which 5% better than the current GM armor with augment (but excluding mana regen, regeneration or damage shield) and has revised slots 2, 3 and 8 (old 8, 9 and 12), I suspect a number of people will actually get very excited about that armor … as a result of the ability to customize it.  The actual improvement in the base armor would not have to be very big as the additional augment slots enable it to become the newest shiny toy on the block. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The end-zone for expansion after that, it would be time to introduce a new set of top end type 2 augments (with the long term goal of moving the stacking effects off the type 3 augment to the type 2 augment).  The rule of thumb for the new type 2 augments could be that DoN base pieces plus the new augment alone would be somewhere around qvic geared in terms of AC, hp/mana/endurance and total resists. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Whenever the level cap is next increased (or when next appropriate), add a new type 3 customizable foci set of augments with the next level of foci which have no stacking effects but leave the base AC/hp/mana/endurance/statistics and resists roughly equal to the current last blood type levels.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The vision associated with this type of itemization is making Everquest raiding more progressive in nature.  Everything the player needs to get to the top of the leaderboards shouldn’t be available from a single expansion.  The model is one of making the player make some real choices and trade-offs with respect to their gearing choices.  The tools used by the developers would be the statistics on the base piece, the stackable effects on the type 2 augments, the non-stackable foci on the type 3 augments and the type 8 augments.  Each subsequent end zone for future expansions would provide significant upgrades for only one of the four basic pieces and provide fillers pieces equivalent to the upgrades from two expansions prior.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Itemization shouldn’t be starting from a blank slate on each expansion.  Players’ play styles differ and what’s important for them to acquire changes over time depending on what they already have.  Moving towards an unified itemization model which incorporates all the tools available to a developer should minimize the necessity of mudflation across the board and provide a coherent model for itemization go forward.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Disadvantages:&lt;br&gt;This would require some developer time.  It would improve some gear from older expansions, including LDoN and DoN (through slot changes).  It is likely to be fairly controversial.  Any time item changes get made, there is a significant risk of errors.  Long term planning of expansion and gear where the augment is an integral part of the equation would actually lead to a step backward in terms of AC, hp and mana on the base gear … but the overall power would increase as the gear got customized.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Message Edited by Msakr on &lt;span class="date_text"&gt;04-05-2006&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="time_text"&gt;01:06 PM&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
